   MOLDAVIA AND REPUBLICS
  </a>
  <a href="#2" id="2">
   Moldavia, acting to defuse one of the Soviet Union's most explosive ethnic conflicts, agreed on Dec. 29, 1990 to comply with a Kremlin order to reconsider its law making Moldavian the republic's official language.
  </a>
  <a href="#3" id="3">
   Ethnic tension has gripped Moldavia, a largely agricultural republic bordering Romania, during its push for independence from the Soviet Union in 1991.
  </a>
  <a href="#4" id="4">
   In the eastern part of Moldavia, more than 300,000 ethnic Russians and Ukrainians have joined in declaring a new republic along the Dneister River.
  </a>
  <a href="#5" id="5">
   The Gagauz, a group of about 150,000 Turkish Christians, declared a new republic in southern Moldavia.
  </a>
